and but it doesn't seem necessary. I’m also pondering potential issues with the Grammar constructor triggering the ErrorManager static initialization, especially with the dynamic report classes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing test coverage rules**\\n\\nI’m contemplating the rule to \\\"keep coverage for each dynamic-access class in its own dedicated Java test file.\\\" If the GrammarReportTest inadvertently covers CodeGenerator via dynamic call sites, that could lead to a violation. It looks like this test could accidentally cover CodeGenerator.loadLanguageTarget if triggered by the Grammar constructor. I need to avoid covering other dynamic-access classes. It’s tricky to test toNotifyString without inadvertently triggering CodeGenerator's presence. I wonder if using a manual fake or a constructed Grammar with language options could help? However, it seems that could lead back to complications with CodeGenerator's coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test focus on active classes**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether I should focus only on the active class, as the user suggested, which makes me wonder if they really care about incidental coverage. It might be possible to avoid covering toNotifyString, but that would leave those call sites uncovered. Perhaps I could implement a Grammar subclass in the test that still interacts with CodeGenerator via the Grammar constructor. Still, I'm a bit concerned about complaints during review. I wonder if using an internal constructor would help? It seems like all options could end up tracking CodeGenerator.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hQVxijYM2Bc2npydXzAoOTYj|fc_0c900ddf1c4ccbcd0169f6a26606d08192b2d7d959d2fa4121", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.antlr/antlr/3.5.2/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 731, "output": 896, "cacheRead": 34816, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 36443,